    "encrypted": "false",
    "embed": "false",
    "long_instructions": "<br/>\r\n\r\nHaley had just finished her history project and was ready to turn it in. Her teacher had shared a Google Drive folder where students could upload their work.\r\n\r\nWhen Haley opened the folder, she saw other students’ files:\r\n\r\n* **Amara's essay** was set to view-only.\r\n* **Jon's essay** required a request for access.\r\n* **Her own essay** was set to \"Anyone with the link can edit.\"\r\n\r\nAt first, Haley didn't notice anything wrong, until she clicked on her own file. Instead of her carefully written paragraphs, the document was now full of SpongeBob quotes. Strangers had clearly found her file and decided to have some fun.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n\r\n#### **What Happened Here?**\r\n\r\nA **misconfiguration** is a mistake or oversight in system settings that makes it easier for attackers to gain access. These issues can happen accidentally or as a result of poor default settings that leave files or systems too open.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 1: Open Chrome**\r\n\r\nChrome will open to a shared Google Drive folder with student submissions.\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 2: Explore the Submissions**\r\n\r\nClick through the files in the folder. Observe how each one is shared and what level of access you have.\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n**Step 3: Decide What to Do**\r\n\r\nHaley now has a problem. Should she restore her project to its original version, change the sharing settings, or report the edits? What steps could prevent this from happening in the future?\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n",
